In Python:

Variables do NOT have types.
Objects have types.
Variables are just names bound to objects.

C++
int x = 10;

x has type int
Memory is allocated for int
You cannot later do:
x = "hello";   // ❌ compile error
Because x is strongly typed.



Python
x = 10
x = "hello"

This is valid.

Why?

Because:
	x is just a name
	It is bound to an object
	That object has the type



x = 10

Step 1:
	Python creates an integer object 10
	That object lives in heap memory

Step 2:
	The name x is created
	x now references that object

